<topic xml:id="openwebui-AI-models-creating"
 role="task" xml:lang="en"
 xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" version="5.2"
 xmlns:its="http://www.w3.org/2005/11/its"
 xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
 xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
 xmlns:trans="http://docbook.org/ns/transclusion">
  <info>
    <title>Creating custom AI models</title>
    <meta name="maintainer" content="tbazant@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract>
<!-- <xi:include href="../snippets/openwebui-intro.xml"/> -->
      <para>
        This procedure shows how to create custom AI models using &openwebui;.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <procedure>
    <itemizedlist>
      <title>Requirements</title>
      <listitem>
        <xi:include href="../snippets/openwebui-requirement-admin-privileges.xml"/>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
    <step>
      <para>
        In the &openwebui; interface, click <guimenu>Workspace</guimenu> in the
        upper part of the left panel.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Select <guimenu>Models</guimenu> in the top menu and click the
        <guimenu>Create a model</guimenu> link under the search bar.
      </para>
      <figure>
        <title>Managing AI models</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject role="fo">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models.png" width="50%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <imageobject role="html">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models.png" width="50%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject role="description"><phrase>Managing AI models</phrase>
          </textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        By clicking the big + sign at the top of the form, you can upload an
        avatar image for your model.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Enter <guimenu>Name</guimenu> of your new model and modify the
        <guimenu>Model ID</guimenu> if you are not happy with the provided one.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Specify the base AI model on which your model will be based on.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step performance="optional">
      <para>
        Enter a short description of your AI model.
      </para>
      <figure>
        <title>Avatar, name and description of a new AI model</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject role="fo">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create1.png" width="50%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <imageobject role="html">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create1.png" width="50%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject role="description"><phrase>Avatar, name and description of a new AI model</phrase>
          </textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
    </step>
    <step performance="optional">
      <para>
        To direct the AI model's responses, specify a <guimenu>System
        Prompt</guimenu>. Find more details about system prompts in
        <link xlink:href="&dsc;/suse-ai/1.0/html/AI-system-prompts/index.html"/>.
      </para>
      <tip>
        <para>
          By clicking the small <guimenu>Show</guimenu> link below the system
          prompt field, you can fine tune the model's behavior by modifying its
          advanced settings.
        </para>
      </tip>
    </step>
    <step performance="optional">
      <para>
        Specify one or more <guimenu>Prompt suggestions</guimenu>. They will be
        shown on the model's chat welcome screen.
      </para>
      <figure>
        <title>System prompt and prompt suggestions</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject role="fo">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create2.png" width="50%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <imageobject role="html">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create2.png" width="50%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject role="description"><phrase>System prompt and prompt suggestions</phrase>
          </textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
    </step>
    <step performance="optional">
      <para>
        To extend the model's knowledge base, select one or more documents or
        collections of documents from the preconfigured list.
      </para>
      <figure>
        <title>Extending the model's knowledge base</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject role="fo">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create4.png" width="60%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <imageobject role="html">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create4.png" width="60%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject role="description"><phrase>Extending the model's knowledge base</phrase>
          </textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
    </step>
    <step performance="optional">
      <para>
        In the <guimenu>Tools</guimenu>, <guimenu>Filters</guimenu>,
        <guimenu>Actions</guimenu> and <guimenu>Capabilities</guimenu> sections,
        activate the items that you want your model to use.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Describe the model with custom tags so that other users can identify it
        easily.
      </para>
      <figure>
        <title>Capabilities and tags</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject role="fo">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create5.png" width="40%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <imageobject role="html">
            <imagedata fileref="openwebui-workspace-models-create5.png" width="40%"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject role="description"><phrase>Capabilities and tags</phrase>
          </textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
      <tip>
        <para>
          To view the JSON representation of your model, click the small
          <guimenu>Show</guimenu> link right of the <guimenu>JSON
          Preview</guimenu> label.
        </para>
      </tip>
      <para>
        Save your changes with the <guimenu>Save &amp; Create</guimenu> button.
      </para>
    </step>
  </procedure>
</topic>
